New York Life Investment Management Announces Executive Changes
Jun 1 17
New York Life Investment Management announced expanded roles for two senior leaders of its executive team. Kirk Lehneis, chief operating officer, adds the retail business, MainStay Funds and IndexIQ, to his portfolio, including global product development and marketing. John Grady, senior managing director and vice chairman of New York Life Investment Management International, will also serve as chief administrative officer, responsible for strategy, mergers and acquisitions, and business development. Mr. Lehneis and Mr. Grady both continue to report to NYLIM CEO, Yie-Hsin Hung. Together, these moves support the company's strategic growth priorities while creating a more integrated management team. Additionally, NYLIM announced that Stephen Fisher, president of MainStay Funds, will retire in September after more than 14 years with the company. Until that time, Mr. Fisher becomes senior advisor to Ms. Hung. NYLIM will be hiring a new head of U.S. Distribution. In the interim, retail distribution roles which previously reported to Mr. Fisher will report to Ms. Hung. Kirk Lehneis. Mr. Lehneis joined New York Life in 2005 and has held a series of senior leadership roles including: strategic planning and implementation in support of NYLIM's strategic growth initiatives across alternatives, international expansion, and exchange traded funds; and heading up mergers and acquisitions, technology initiatives and training in support of the business. John Grady. Mr. Grady has held a number of senior advisory roles at the company including senior advisor to the president of New York Life Investments Group. He joined New York Life's asset management business as chief financial officer, after several years at New York Life Insurance Company where he was senior vice president responsible for Mergers and Acquisitions and the Treasury Department.


